# Our Story
A family tradition of Italian cooking, rooted in love and passed down through generations.
:::

## Our History

Giuseppe Rossi arrived in Portland in 1982 with little more than a suitcase and his grandmother's recipe book. After three years working in local kitchens, he opened a small trattoria on Main Street with twelve tables and a dream.

What started as a humble neighborhood spot quickly became a Portland institution. Word spread about Giuseppe's hand-rolled pasta, slow-simmered sauces, and the warmth you felt the moment you walked through the door. Four decades later, that same spirit fills every corner of the restaurant.

Today, Giuseppe's daughter Elena and son Marco carry the legacy forward, honoring the recipes and traditions their father brought from the hills of Tuscany.

## Chef Elena Rossi

::: bg https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1577219491135-ce391730fb2c?w=1200&q=80
# Trained in Tuscany. Rooted in Portland.
Elena spent five years apprenticing in Florence and Bologna before returning home to lead Giuseppe's kitchen.
:::

## Our Philosophy

|||>

### Farm to Table

We source produce from local Oregon farms within 50 miles of our kitchen. Every morning, our team selects the freshest seasonal ingredients at the Portland Farmers Market.

|||

### Handmade Pasta

Our pasta is made fresh daily using traditional techniques. From tagliatelle to ravioli, every strand and shape is crafted by hand in our open kitchen.

|||

### Slow-Simmered Sauces

Our signature Bolognese simmers for eight hours. Our marinara uses San Marzano tomatoes imported directly from a family farm near Naples.

|||<

